===Etymology===
From the Greek [[Αβραάμ]] (Avraám), through Late Latin; from the Hebrew [[אברהם|אַבְרָהָם]] ('Abrāhām). Possibly compounded from [[אב|אָב]] (av = 'father') + [[המון]] (hamon = 'multitude'): father of a multitude of nations; or from Hebrew [[אברם|אַבְרָם]], 'high father', from [[אב|אָב]] (av = 'father') + [[רם|רָם]] (ram = 'high', 'lofty').

===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}

# A prophet in the [[Old Testament]]; Semitic [[patriarch]], father of the Jewish patriarch [[Isaac]] (by his wife [[Sarah]]) and the Arabic patriarch [[Ishmael]] (by his concubine [[Hagar]]).
#*And these are the days of the years of '''Abraham's''' life which he lived, an hundred and threescore and fifteen years.'' Genesis 25:7''
# A male [[given name]].
# A [[surname]].

